<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900821-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>900821-0044.</DOCID><HL>   The President's Vacation   Is Raising Some Eyebrows</HL><DATE>08/21/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   MDEST</CO><GV>EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><LP>   Although an overwhelming 72% of Americans back PresidentBush's actions in the deserts of the Middle East, they'reless sure about his conduct in Kennebunkport, Maine.   Only 53% approved of his taking time to vacation at hisseacoast home just now, with 39% disapproving, in a polltaken over the weekend before the hostage drama escalated.Television news has juxtaposed Mr. Bush playing golf withpoignant interviews with relatives of Americans presumablybeing held hostage.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;I was saddened to see . . . Mr. Bush playing golf andgoing fishing after having sent U.S. troops overseas,&quot; saidLawrence Naumoff, 44, a Chapel Hill, N.C., novelist. &quot;It wasa vision of the old-fashioned ugly American who doesn'treflect on what his actions have caused.&quot;   However, Edith Seibert, a housewife from Hermitage, Pa.,said, &quot;His mind is much clearer up there {in Maine} withouteverybody in Washington beating on him to make a militarystrike.&quot;   Mr. Bush broke off his vacation for the second timeyesterday to meet with advisers in Washington, then returnedto Maine. The White House says that this is a workingvacation and that, thanks to sophisticated communications,Mr. Bush can manage the nation's affairs as well in Maine asin Washington.   (See related story: &quot;Home Front: Public Backs Dispatch OfTroops to Mideast But Fears for Outcome --- Many SeeDrawn-Out Affair, And Suddenly a Majority Expects a U.S.Recession --- Lessons From the Korea Crisis&quot; -- WSJ August21, 1990)</TEXT></DOC>